{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476550"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13802"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13802"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.47,0.03,0.34,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49011"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6419"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13802"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34029"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"627"},{"type":"tags","id":"799"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13014"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49011"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-month-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parents due to a lesion on her right eyelid. The parents report that it appeared shortly after birth and has been gradually growing. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lesion is red, raised, and soft to touch (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate surgical excision","Observation and regular follow-up","Topical corticosteroids","Propranolol","Referral for laser therapy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image depicts an infantile haemangioma in the periocular region. Given its location and the patient\u0027s age, \u003Cstrong\u003Epropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. Infantile haemangiomas typically undergo rapid growth until about 12 months of age, followed by a slow involution phase. In this case, the periocular location poses a significant risk to visual development if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation and regular follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E, while appropriate for many uncomplicated infantile haemangiomas, is not the best choice for periocular lesions due to the risk of visual axis obstruction and induced astigmatism. These complications can lead to amblyopia if not addressed promptly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate surgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as the first-line treatment for infantile haemangiomas, especially in young infants. Surgery carries risks and may result in scarring, which can be particularly problematic in the periocular area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are sometimes used for small, superficial haemangiomas, but they are less effective than propranolol and carry a risk of local and systemic side effects. They are not the preferred treatment for periocular haemangiomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for laser therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is generally reserved for residual telangiectasias after involution or for thin, superficial haemangiomas. It is not typically used as an initial treatment for proliferating infantile haemangiomas, especially those in high-risk locations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPropranolol, a beta-blocker, has become the first-line treatment for problematic infantile haemangiomas since its serendipitous discovery in 2008. It is particularly effective when started early in the proliferative phase and has shown excellent results for periocular haemangiomas. The treatment is generally well-tolerated, with a good safety profile when administered under medical supervision. Regular follow-up with both a paediatrician and an ophthalmologist is crucial to monitor the response to treatment and ensure normal visual development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Infantile haemangiomas typically undergo a natural course of rapid growth until 12 months of age, followed by spontaneous involution.","Periocular haemangiomas require prompt treatment due to the risk of visual axis obstruction and astigmatism.","Propranolol is the first-line treatment for problematic infantile haemangiomas, particularly those in high-risk locations such as the periocular region."],"references":[]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13802"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20745"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20745"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JM3Yx2YxqkrRjB7jQ3CT4YUEXgEQBp.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JM3Yx2YxqkrRjB7jQ3CT4YUEXgEQBp.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":502,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-22T14:22:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-22T14:22